5|$|Reed v. Reed (1971), which {{struck down}} an Idaho probate law favoring men, {{was the first}} {{decision}} in which the Court ruled that arbitrary gender discrimination violated the <b>Equal</b> <b>Protection</b> Clause. In Craig v. Boren (1976), the Court ruled that statutory or administrative sex classifications had {{to be subjected to}} an intermediate standard of judicial review. Reed and Craig later served as precedents to strike down a number of state laws discriminating by gender.|$|E
